Novel polybasic protein cleavage site (aa seq RRAR) that can be processed by furin-like proteases, not present in the virus from SARS 2013 outbreak, situated on the S1 side of site where a human protease cleaves viral S protein into S1 and S2 facilitating infection. See also http://www.chinaxiv.org/abs/202002.00062, https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0820-9.pdf, and news article https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00660-x.  See https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.04.10.036533v1.full.pdf for the structural interaction between the furin protein and this site on the viral S protein.

This base of the viral mRNA is sometimes translated twice by the ribosome due to programmed -1 ribosomal frameshifting. This allows translation to continue for almost the entire length of the remaining RNA, instead of hitting a stop codon very quickly, as it does without the frameshift. The reading frame downstream of this site is shifted by -1 bases relative to the reading frame upstream of this position.

30bp deletion at the S1/S2 junction removes the PRRA motif from this region of the spike protein. Infection with this mutation in hamsters does not cause severe pathological changes associated with WT SARS-CoV-2 infection. Screening for this variant in asymptomatic cases could have important implications for Del-mut variants as an attenuated vaccine.

Non-structural Leader protein (NSP1) inhibits translation by binding to the 40S ribosomal subunit and induces a template-dependence endonucleolytic cleavage of host mRNAs. It also inhibits type I interferon expression and host antiviral signaling pathways, therefore inhibiting host innate immunity.
NSP2 is a nonstructural protein that interacts with host PHB and PHB2, impacting host cell survival signaling pathway.

NSP3 is a nonstructural protein that is involved in proteolysis, involving single-stranded RNA binding, cysteine-type peptidase activity, RNA-directed 5'-3' RNA polymerase activity, and nucleic acid binding.
NSP4 is a nonstructural protein involved in assembly of virally-induced cytoplasmic double-membrane vescicles, which are necessary for viral replication.
3C-like proteinase is a nonstructural protein involved in viral protein processing in replication.
NSP6 is a nonstructural protein that can increase cellular gene synthesis and induce apoptosis. It interferes with host antiviral responses by inhibiting synthesis and signalling of IFN-beta.

NSP7 is a nonstructural protein that activates RNA-synthesizing activity. It interacts with NSP8 to for a hexadecamer that may participate in viral replication as a primase.  InterPro predicts its functions to be omega peptidase activity, cysteine-type endopeptidase activity, and transferase activity.
NSP8 is a nonstructural protein that forms a hexadecamer with NSP7. As a monomer, it may not be biologically relevant.
NSP9 is a nonstrcutural single-stranded RNA-binding viral protein that is involved in RNA synthesis.
NSP10 is a nonstructural protein involved in viral mRNA cap methylation. It binds to NSP16 to form a complex exhibiting RNA cap (nucleoside-2'-O)-methyltransferase activity.
RNA-dependent RNA polymerase functions as RNA-directed 5’-3’ RNA polymerase activity, RNA binding, and ATP binding. NSP7 and NSP8 activate RNA-synthesizing functions of Pol/RdRp.
Helicase protein has a zinc-binding domain in N-terminus with RNA and DNA unwinding activities with 5’ to 3’ polarity. Activity dependent on magnesium.
3’-5’ exonuclease is a nonstructural protein that exhibits exoribonuclease activity on ssRNA and dsRNA in a 3’ to 5’ direction. It also exhibits N7-guanine methyltransferase activity.
EndoRNAse is a nonstructural protein that is a manganese-dependent, uridylate-specific enzyme leaving 2’-3’-cyclic phosphates 5’ to the cleaved bond.
2’-O-ribose methyltransferase is a heterodimer formed from NSP10 and NSP16. Its topology matches those of dengue virus NS5 N-terminal domain and of vaccinia virus VP39 MTases.

The S protein is a structural protein known as the spike glycoprotein. Spike protein S1 attaches the virus to cell membrane by interacting with the host receptor (ACE2 and CLEC4M/DC-SIGNR receptors). S2 mediates fusion of virus and cellular membrane by acting as a class I viral fusion protein. S2’ is unmasked following S2 cleavage occurring upon virus endocytosis, acting as a viral fusion peptide.
ORF3a protein is a papain-Ike protease part of Protein 3a family, which is a pro-apotosis-inducing protein.

Envelope protein (E protein) is a structural protein well conserved among coronavirus strains. It is a small, integral membrane protein that acts as a viroporin by oligomerizing after insertion in host membrane to create a hydrophilic pore that allows ion transport. It forms a calcium permeable channel in ER/Golgi intermediate compartment membranes, resulting in exacerbated inflammation and immunopathology.

Membrane glycoprotein (M protein) is the most abundant structural protein, defining the shape of viral envelope. Interaction of S and M proteins is required. It is the central organizer of viral assembly, interacting with all other structural proteins.
ORF6 protein is a nonstructural protein, highly conserved among SARS-related coronaviruses.

ORF7a is a nonstructural, unique type I transmembrane protein. It has binding activity to integrin I domains, and contains a motif shown to mediate COPII dependent transport out of the ER. It is targeted to the Golgi apparatus.
ORF7b is a nonstructural protein. Its transmembrane domain is essential to retain protein in Golgi compartment.
ORF8 protein is accessory protein 8 with two conserved sequence motifs: EDPCP and INCQ. It may modulate viral pathogenicity or replication in favor of human adaptation.

Nucleocapsid phosphoprotein (N protein) binds to viral RNA genome. N proteins interact with NSP3 and are recruited to replication-transcription complexes. It has a three domain structure of N1b and N2b linked by N2a. N2a has a SR-rich region which is phosphorylated by host glycogen synthase kinase-3, allowing N protein to associate with helicase and permit template read-through.
ORF10 protein

AAC-->UUU. Rapidly emerging variant that extends lower stem of Stem Loop 1 in 5'UTR by 3 base pairs, stabilizing the duplex due to increased base pairing interactions. This variant has implications for development of drugs/therapies that may target regulatory RNA structures, since the emerging variations could cause drug resistance.

C-->A. Rapidly emerging variant that extends the lower stem of Stem Loop 1 an additional base pair, increasing stability. It is most likely a secondary mutation to A34A35C36--->U34U35U36. This variant has implications for development of drugs/therapies that may target regulatory RNA structures, since the emerging variations could cause drug resistance.

C-->U. Rapidly emerging variant in the Stem Loop 5b region at 5'UTR/ORF1a junction. Its high abundance suggests it may be a hot spot for viral genome editing by host defense enzymes. This variant has implications for development of drugs/therapies that may target regulatory RNA structures, since the emerging variations could cause drug resistance.

C-->U. Rapidly emerging variant in Stem 2 of the frameshifting RNA pseudoknot at the ORF1a/1b junction. C13536 normally forms a Watson-Crick pair with G13493, instead they now form a wobble pair which likely reduces stability of stem 2 due to differing backbone geometry. This is expected to cause less efficient -1 programmed ribosomal frameshifting, which may block viral infection. This variant has implications for development of drugs/therapies that may target regulatory RNA structures, since the emerging variations could cause drug resistance.

G-->A. Rapidly emerging variant in the 5' portion of 3'UTR. Disrupts G:C pair in extended BSL (bulged stem loop) molecular switch conformer that could potentially favor the alternate PK (pseudoknot) structure. Mutations that stabilize one form over the other prevent viral replication, suggesting competition between two structures plays a regulatory role in antigenomic RNA synthesis. This variant has implications for development of drugs/therapies that may target regulatory RNA structures, since the emerging variations could cause drug resistance.

G-->C. Rapidly emerging variant in the S2M structure in the HVR (highly variable region) downstream of 3’UTR pseudoknot. Forms a noncanonical G:A pair normally, but substitution of C in place of G disrupts hydrogen bonding and destabilizes S2M tertiary structure. This variant has implications for development of drugs/therapies that may target regulatory RNA structures, since the emerging variations could cause drug resistance.

G-->U. Rapidly emerging variant in the S2M structure in the HVR (highly variable region) downstream of 3’UTR pseudoknot. This base pairs through its Watson-Crick face with a cytidine residue and interacts with the C of a parallel G:C pair. The U variation is incompatible with both the canonical and non-canonical pairings at this position and is likely to be highly destabilizing to the fold. This variant has implications for development of drugs/therapies that may target regulatory RNA structures, since the emerging variations could cause drug resistance.

Forward (+ strand aln) 2kb primer sequence for long amplicon tiling multiplex approach using nanopore sequencing to recover whole SARS-CoV-2 genome. This protocol is quick and versatile, as it is applicable to different sequencing methods (Nanopore, Illumina, and/or Sanger). The unique primer set is composed of 17 primer pairs, covering 30kb of the genome, with each primer pair covering 2kb of the genome with a 100 bp overlap of amplicons. The entire list of primer pairs can be found at this link: https://www.biorxiv.org/content/biorxiv/early/2020/05/01/2020.04.30.069039/T1.medium.gif.

A potential G-quadruplex (PGR) on (-) sense viral strand, predicted by pqsfinder, QGRS Mapper, and G4CatchAll. G-quadruplexes are non-canonical nucleic acid structures usually formed in G-rich regions in an RNA strand, and are formed when four guanines making up G-quartets are connected via Hoogsteen pairs. They regulate viral processes, making them candidates for antiviral drug targets. g4s at 3' end of (-)sense strand could inhibit RNA synthesis by reducing RdRp activity. 24 PGRs predicted, the rest are linked here: https://www.biorxiv.org/content/biorxiv/early/2020/06/05/2020.06.05.135749/T1/graphic-2.large.jpg?width=800&height=600&carousel=1, and here: https://www.biorxiv.org/content/biorxiv/early/2020/06/05/2020.06.05.135749/T1/graphic-3.large.jpg?width=800&height=600&carousel=1

A potential G-quadruplex (PGR) on (+) sense viral strand, predicted by pqsfinder, QGRS Mapper, and G4CatchAll. G-quadruplexes are non-canonical nucleic acid structures usually formed in G-rich regions in an RNA strand, and are formed when four guanines making up G-quartets are connected via Hoogsteen pairs. They regulate viral processes, making them candidates for antiviral drug targets. Translation of some viral proteins requires human ribosomes, so stabilizing G4s could repress translation of viral proteins. 24 PGRs predicted, the rest are linked here: https://www.biorxiv.org/content/biorxiv/early/2020/06/05/2020.06.05.135749/T1/graphic-2.large.jpg?width=800&height=600&carousel=1 , and here: https://www.biorxiv.org/content/biorxiv/early/2020/06/05/2020.06.05.135749/T1/graphic-3.large.jpg?width=800&height=600&carousel=1

This amino acid residue (2337K) is one of 8 key amino acid residues in SUD reported to be associated with G-quadruplex binding affinity, and is conserved across almost 17,000 SARS-CoV-2 samples across countries all over the world, The SUD (SARS Unique Domain) in SARS is conserved in SARS-CoV-2, among other betacoronaviruses. The SUD is thought to be related to viral pathogenicity and displays binding preference to G-quadruplexes; this binding can affect translation, impairing immune response of host cells. Targeting G-quadruplexes is a promising antiviral strategy.
